In colaboration with the CREES foudation we aim to find out whether medium-large mammal abundance  differs between forest streams and forest habitat, and whether this difference in abundance and diversity differs depending on the disturbance history of the habitat. This research wil be done within the confounds of the CREES reserve, using trapcams along small forest streams. The data that is gathered from this website will be used to compare with our data so that we can add some additional power to the research.This research could alter the way we perceive small forest streams and their role in the ecology of medium-large mammals and their potential for conservation of ecosystems.

I am interested in examining controls on the abundance and biodiversity of nitrogen fixing trees across the Amazon basin using forest and soil data from the RAINFOR network and the TEAM network.  I am a postdoctoral research associate at Princeton University studying interactions between carbon and nutrient cycles with a focus on symbiotic nitrogen fixation.  I am also working with Lars Hedin, who is a professor at Princeton University.  His research group has been interested in nitrogen fixation and biogeochemistry over the past decade.  Lars and I have recently begun a collaborative project with Jon Lloyd, Beto Quesada and Oliver Phillips and a large number of principal investigators from the RAINFOR network on nitrogen fixation.

Based on our interest in symbiotic nitrogen fixation across tropical forests ecosystems, we would like to analyze how the distribution and diversity of nitrogen fixers varies with soils and disturbance across the RAINFOR plots.  Central to this effort is to test predictions from a model on nitrogen fixation that we have developed.  Much theory exists about the function of and controls on nitrogen fixation in tropical forests, yet no study has examined such a large dataset of trees and soils across such a broad environmental gradient as the RAINFOR consortium.  

This means that we are seeking information on the abundance and species of nitrogen fixers across plots.  We are working with data from ~120 RAINFOR plots, and would like to include data from the TEC-01 through TEC-06 plots that are part of the TEAM network.

The goal of the study is to assess the extent to which tropical biota may be vulnerable to global warming. The methodology for this project is relatively straightforward.  At the outset, we will conduct a meta-analysis of published and unpublished studies of species distributions in the tropics with respect to large-scale elevational gradients.  
Once a database of the original data has been compiled, we will assess, for each study, the proportion of species that are confined to a particular elevational zone.  At a minimum, we will divide the elevational samples into lowland (<300 m elevation), lower mid-elevation (300-1000 m), upper-mid elevation (1000-2000), and high-elevation (>2000 m) samples.  Any study sites with non-trivial habitat disturbance will be discarded from the analysis.  We will include only studies that used a consistent sampling methodology to sample a particular taxonomic group and that had roughly similar sampling intensities at each altitude (the second of these assumptions is less important unless easily-sampled species are biased toward elevational specialists or generalists).  
Once the dataset has been compiled and critically examined, we will use log-linear models to assess the proportion of elevational specialists among different elevational zones, stratifying our analyses by (a) major taxonomic groupings (e.g. angiosperm trees, palms, forbs, birds, nonflying mammals, bats, reptiles and amphibians, insects) or functional groups (e.g. plants, endothermic animals, ectothermic animals), and (b) geographic region (e.g. Asian, Australasian, African, and Neotropical sites).   By evaluating the data in various ways, we will search for underlying patterns in the dataset.  
In this way we hope to test two key hypotheses.  First, do the major elevational zones in the tropics differ in the proportion of elevational specialists that they sustain?  Second, do particular taxa, functional groups, or geographic regions show conspicuous differences from the overall trends?
